<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>William of Ockham</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Fri Aug 16, 2002; substantive revision Wed Sep 11, 2024</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
William of Ockham (c. 1287&ndash;1347) is among the most prominent
figures in the history of philosophy during the Late Middle Ages along
with Thomas Aquinas and John Duns Scotus. He is probably best known
today for his espousal of metaphysical nominalism. Indeed, the
principle known as &ldquo;Ockham&rsquo;s Razor&rdquo; is named after
him. But Ockham held important, often influential views not only in
metaphysics but also in all other major areas of medieval
philosophy&mdash;logic, physics or natural philosophy, theory of
knowledge, ethics, and political philosophy&mdash;as well as in
theology.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
